QEMU/Wayland pointer research, 2026-07-21

Confirmed upstream behavior:

* QEMU GTK uses pointer warping while establishing and maintaining relative
  pointer grabs. Its first relative-mode click starts the grab and is not
  forwarded to the guest.
  https://github.com/qemu/qemu/blob/master/ui/gtk.c

* GTK 3.24.52's Wayland gdk_wayland_device_warp() is empty. QEMU cannot rely
  on it to recenter the pointer under native Wayland.
  https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gtk/-/blob/3.24.52/gdk/wayland/gdkdevice-wayland.c

* QEMU SDL also enables relative mouse mode and relies on pointer warping.
  SDL documents Wayland limits around global cursor coordinates and warping.
  https://github.com/qemu/qemu/blob/master/ui/sdl2.c
  https://wiki.libsdl.org/SDL3/README-wayland

This matches local tests: GTK, GTK/XWayland, and SDL all accepted keyboard
input but did not deliver usable pointer input to either published guest
artifact. No evidence supports guest-agent, SPICE, guest packages, KVM, or
the guest kernel as a fix.

Next diagnostics:
  * test from an actual GNOME Xorg session;
  * capture short native-Wayland QEMU traces with WAYLAND_DEBUG=1;
  * compare whether wl_pointer button/motion events arrive. If they do not,
    report to Mutter/Wayland; if they do and QEMU does not forward them,
    report to QEMU.

Local trace result:
  QEMU received wl_pointer enter, leave, motion, and button events from the
  native Wayland compositor (874 motion events and 10 button events during
  the short manual test). Guest pointer input still did not work. The next
  report belongs with QEMU's native-Wayland relative-grab forwarding path,
  not the image or host event delivery.

Guest and QMP checks:
  The published ISO and qcow2 have matching kernel, libinput, Mutter, GNOME
  Shell, GTK, and Plymouth packages. Neither has qemu-guest-agent or
  spice-vdagent installed.
  QMP reports a current non-absolute `QEMU PS/2 Mouse`. A relative motion
  and click submitted through QMP's input-send-event command were accepted.
  This proves QEMU's emulated mouse input core accepts events independently
  of the native GTK window. It does not by itself prove guest-side rendering
  of the injected movement.

Second independent assessment:
  QEMU GTK uses an internal pointer-owner state and intentionally consumes the
  first relative-mode click to start grabbing. It relies on pointer warping
  to recenter and restore that grab. GTK's Wayland warp implementation is a
  no-op, which can leave QEMU's internal grab state inconsistent with the
  compositor. QEMU does not check the GTK seat-grab result before recording
  its pointer as grabbed.

  This is not verified as a QEMU 11-only regression. QEMU issue #3192
  describes the same Wayland-versus-X11 grab failure against QEMU 10.1 and
  remains open:
  https://gitlab.com/qemu-project/qemu/-/issues/3192

  Highest-value next test: run the unchanged QEMU command in a real GNOME
  Xorg session. If it works there, the Wayland grab/warp path is confirmed.
  An older QEMU build is a useful A/B test, but not proof without repeatable
  results. For an upstream report, enable QEMU trace events `gd_grab`,
  `gd_ungrab`, `gd_motion_event`, `input_event_rel`, and `input_event_btn`.
